kb:predicate-manager a ktype:Feature;
    rdfs:label "Predicate Manager";
    kpred:has-status "production";
    kpred:tested-by "src/lib/rdf/__tests__/predicates.test.ts";
    kpred:has-file "src/lib/rdf/predicates.ts";
    kpred:description "View all predicates with counts, rename, merge. Schema evolution tool. Rename and merge are PLANNED before they are applied (rdf/predicates.ts: planRename / planMerge), so the UI can warn before mutating: standard-vocabulary terms are refused, a rename that collides with an existing predicate is named as the merge it really is, and statements that would become exact twins are dropped rather than written.";
    kpred:known-issue "FIXED 2026-07-12 — THREE defects, all found by the first test ever written for it. (1) RENAME DESTROYED STANDARD VOCABULARY: the new IRI's namespace was chosen as isMetaPredicate(old) ? META_PREFIX : PREDICATE_PREFIX, with no third case — so renaming rdfs:label, skos:broader or dcterms:created (all of which appear the moment a user imports real Turtle) rewrote them into urn:kbase:predicate/<slug>, silently converting an interoperable standard term into a private one. The graph stops meaning what it said, and no export carries that meaning anywhere. (2) RENAME ONTO AN EXISTING PREDICATE SILENTLY MERGED, irreversibly, from a control labelled 'rename'. (3) MERGE CREATED DUPLICATE STATEMENTS: merging likes into loves when both already asserted (x,.,y) left two identical triples. The logic lived inline in PredicateManager.svelte, which is why all three survived — extracting it to a pure module is what made them findable.";
    kpred:principle "A destructive action must never be silent. Refuse, or warn, but never quietly do something other than what the control is labelled.".
kb:content-safety a ktype:Feature;
    kpred:tested-by "src/lib/safety/__tests__/content-policy.test.ts";
    rdfs:label "Content Safety";
    kpred:has-status "production";
    kpred:principle "Ethics AND morals, not just law. Laws vary across borders and legality is a floor, not a ceiling — Reckons.AI applies a baseline ethical standard (no incitement, no hate, no sexualization of minors) regardless of local legality. Some things simply should not be broadcast publicly.", "Responsibility model: Reckons.AI is a neutral, local-first TOOL — the user owns and is responsible for the content they create and share. The app makes a good-faith EFFORT to protect users and keep the worst content off the public web, but is not responsible for user-generated content. Documented for humans in SAFETY.md (repo root).";
    kpred:description "Ethics preamble in all LLM prompts (ETHICS_PREAMBLE, src/lib/safety/content-policy.ts). Content classifier (blocked/mature/none) filters blocked content on ingest; mature is flagged. Export advisory headers warn recipients. Local-first: nothing leaves the device unless the user connects an integration.";
    kpred:has-part kb:publish-safety-gate, kb:verified-badge.
kb:publish-safety-gate a ktype:Feature;
    kpred:tested-by "src/lib/publish/__tests__/publish-gate.test.ts";
    kpred:show-on-landing "true";
    kpred:landing-label "Publish safety gate";
    kpred:landing-note "We gate only what we carry — export is always yours, whatever it contains";
    rdfs:label "Publish Safety Gate";
    kpred:feature-id "F66";
    kpred:has-status "functional";
    kpred:done "src/lib/publish/publish-gate.ts (gatePublish, PublishRefusedError); wired into publishSiteToGitHub — the MEDIATED path — and deliberately NOT into exportSiteZip, which is user-export. Coercion-signature + adult detection in safety/content-policy.ts (classifyForDistribution). 11 tests.";
    kpred:part-of kb:content-safety;
    kpred:principle "PRIVATE sharing is the user's to manage (handing someone a .ttl is like emailing a file — the app doesn't police it). PUBLIC publishing to the open web is GATED: make a good-faith effort to block publicly sharing graphs that incite violence or are otherwise illegal or hateful.", "GATE ONLY WHAT WE CARRY (Option C, 2026-07-12 — see kb:adult-content-policy). The gate refuses to CARRY, it never refuses to LET THE USER HAVE: user-export is always available, whatever the graph contains. It also asks NO QUESTION — no purpose declaration, no attestation, no terms to accept — because a gate that accepts an explanation is a gate anyone can talk their way past.";
    kpred:scope "Refuses at mediated distribution: (1) Tier 1 always — minors, NCII, sextortion/blackmail, incitement, mass-casualty weapons; (2) Tier 2 adult content — declined with a plain 'export it and self-host' message, no judgment and no appeal. Tier 3 passes.";
    kpred:description "Before a graph is published to the open web (publishSiteToGitHub / any public target), run it through the same classifier (classifyStatement / filterBlockedStatements) and REFUSE to publish when blocked content is present — with a clear explanation, not a silent drop. Distinct from the existing export ADVISORY (which warns): the publish gate BLOCKS. Also leans on the natural barrier — Reckons.AI hosts nothing, so public publishing requires the user's OWN domain/hosting/file-sharing (Cloudflare, GitHub Pages, a Git host), which limits casual/anonymous abuse and makes the publisher accountable through their own provider. Builds on content-safety; extends site-export.ts.";
    kpred:relates-to kb:graph-publishing;
    kpred:gates kb:graph-publishing, kb:published-ttl, kb:published-graph-exchange, kb:share-links, kb:read-only-guest, kb:kb-publication.
kb:data-egress-model a ktype:Concept;
    rdfs:label "Data egress model (export is a right, distribution is a privilege)";
    kpred:part-of kb:content-safety;
    kpred:description "Classifies every feature by where user data can travel, so the graph can answer 'what leaves the device, and are we the one carrying it?'. kpred:data-egress takes one of: none (stays in IndexedDB); user-export (plain text/TTL to the user's own disk — a RIGHT, never blocked, advisory header only, no lock-in); mediated-distribution (Reckons.AI is the intermediary delivering content to a third party or the open web — publish, share link, exchange, guest view — BLOCKING gate); third-party-service (an opt-in integration's servers, e.g. Drive/n8n/GitHub — gated by explicit user connect + advisory, blocking for public targets). Only mediated-distribution and third-party-service require kpred:gated-by; user-export must NOT be gated, and a lint that demanded one would be a bug.";
    kpred:egress-value "none", "user-export", "mediated-distribution", "third-party-service";
    kpred:principle "Export is a RIGHT: the user's graph is the user's, in a plain, portable, non-proprietary format. Reckons.AI never withholds a user's own data from them, whatever it contains.", "Distribution is a PRIVILEGE: when the app is the intermediary handing content to someone else, it is a participant in that delivery and gates accordingly. Once a file has left as a user-export, what happens next is the user's responsibility, not a control we pretend to have.";
    kpred:invariant "data-egress in {mediated-distribution, third-party-service} => kpred:gated-by is required, and the gate's lifecycle status must be >= the gated feature's status.", "data-egress = user-export => NO blocking gate. Advisory only (scanForExportAdvisory).".
kb:adult-content-policy a ktype:Feature;
    kpred:tested-by "src/lib/publish/__tests__/publish-gate.test.ts", "src/lib/safety/__tests__/content-policy.test.ts";
    rdfs:label "Adult content policy (gate only what we carry)";
    kpred:feature-id "F66.1";
    kpred:has-status "functional";
    kpred:done "classifyForDistribution: allow | decline (Tier 2 adult — we do not carry it, user exports and self-hosts) | refuse (Tier 1 — coercion signature, CSAM, NCII). Detection targets STRUCTURE not explicitness, so a novelist is never treated as a blackmailer. No purpose field, no attestation, no terms: context is never an input to the gate.";
    kpred:part-of kb:publish-safety-gate;
    kpred:relates-to kb:data-egress-model;
    kpred:decided "Option C (2026-07-12): Reckons.AI offers NO mediated distribution channel for adult content. Authoring, storage, and user-export are entirely unimpeded; only mediated distribution is refused.";
    kpred:description "Applies at MEDIATED DISTRIBUTION only — never at authoring, never at storage, never at user-export. TIER 1 (refused everywhere we are in the loop, and refused at generation by the ETHICS_PREAMBLE): sexualization of minors; non-consensual intimate content of real people; sextortion/blackmail; incitement; mass-casualty weapons instructions. TIER 2 ADULT (explicit fiction between adults, graphic fictional violence): NOT MEDIATED. The publish gate declines to carry it and says so plainly — 'Reckons.AI won't publish this for you; export it and host it yourself.' No moral judgment, no accusation, no appeal process, and crucially no questionnaire to game. TIER 3: mediated freely. A false positive costs the user one export and a self-host, so over-blocking is cheap; that is what makes this workable with an imperfect classifier.";
    kpred:principle "Gate only what we carry. Export is a right; distribution is a privilege; we decline to be the intermediary for adult material rather than pretending to adjudicate it.", "Context is never an input to the gate. A gate that accepts a stated purpose is a gate anyone can talk their way past — so we ask nothing, and there is nothing to lie about.", "Tier 1 is principled, not squeamish: it is exactly the set where the harm lands on a THIRD PARTY WHO DID NOT CONSENT. Fiction between consenting adults has no victim; content aimed at a real person does.";
    kpred:remaining "Tier 1 detection should target the COERCION SIGNATURE (a real identifiable person + intimate material + a threat + a demand), which is structural and detectable independently of explicitness — unlike 'classify smut', which simultaneously over-blocks romance authors and under-blocks abuse.";
    kpred:known-gap "The current classifier (content-policy.ts MATURE_PATTERNS) matches DESCRIPTIONS of content — the literal phrases 'sexually explicit', 'pornographic' — not content itself. Actual explicit prose is not detected, while a triple merely SAYING a document is erotic gets flagged. It must not be described as a content filter until rewritten.";
    kpred:consequence "No accounts, no server, no attestation records, no PII retention, no age-verification surface. The traceability problem in COUNSEL-BRIEF.md §6 is DISSOLVED rather than solved: there is nothing to trace because there is no claim to lie about.";
    kpred:depends-on kb:publish-safety-gate.
kb:verified-badge a ktype:Feature;
    rdfs:label "Verified Badge";
    kpred:feature-id "F67";
    kpred:has-status "speculative";
    kpred:part-of kb:content-safety;
    kpred:description "A positive trust signal: a verified badge for a reviewed, accountable publisher or graph — distinct from the anonymous, un-hosted default. Rewards good-faith authors who put their name/domain behind a published graph, and gives readers a signal of provenance. Open question: what does verification attest (identity? a content review? a stable domain?) and who issues it.".
kb:passage-grounding a ktype:Feature;
    rdfs:label "Passage Grounding";
    kpred:has-status "production";
    kpred:tested-by "src/lib/rdf/__tests__/grounding.test.ts", "src/lib/integrations/llm/__tests__/extractor.test.ts";
    kpred:has-file "src/lib/rdf/grounding.ts";
    kpred:description "Every extracted triple carries an excerpt: the verbatim source sentence it was derived from. The excerpt is now VERIFIED against the source text — if the quote does not occur there, it is dropped and the statement's confidence is penalised (x0.6). Matching forgives cosmetic differences a reasonable reader would ignore (smart quotes, en/em dashes, wrapped whitespace, case) but nothing else, so a changed word or an invented sentence still fails. Where no source text is available the excerpt is marked unverifiable rather than accused: silence is not evidence of forgery. Persists via meta:excerpt in TTL reification.";
    kpred:known-issue "FIXED 2026-07-12 — CITATIONS WERE NEVER CHECKED. The extraction prompt instructs the model 'copy it exactly - do not paraphrase', and nothing in the pipeline ever verified that it had. triplesToStatements stored whatever excerpt the model returned, and did not even RECEIVE the source text, so it structurally could not check. A model that paraphrased or invented a quote had it rendered to the user as provenance. Small models paraphrase constantly, so this was not hypothetical. For an app whose pitch is 'knowledge graph - provenance - trust', a FABRICATED CITATION is the worst failure available: the user checks the receipt, the receipt looks right, and it is a forgery. Now verified at ingest; a fabricated excerpt is DROPPED rather than displayed, because showing no citation is honest and showing a forged one is not.";
    kpred:principle "Show the user no citation rather than a forged one.".
