kb:history-mode a ktype:Feature;
    kpred:tested-by "src/lib/storage/__tests__/history.test.ts";
    kpred:has-file "src/lib/storage/history.ts";
    kpred:known-issue "FIXED 2026-07-13 — HISTORY MODE COULD NOT SHOW YOU ANYTHING YOU HAD DELETED. The past was rebuilt by FILTERING the current statement set, but deletion is a hard db.statements.delete(id), so a fact deleted since T is not in that set and could never be filtered back IN. Scrubbing to a time when a fact plainly existed showed a graph without it; the 'was it deleted before T?' branch was unreachable dead code. The one thing a history feature exists to do — show you what you have lost — was the one thing it could not do. It now replays the CHANGELOG and resurrects deleted facts from the tombstone ({s,p,o} snapshot written at delete time), so add → delete → re-add resolves correctly at every instant.", "FIXED 2026-07-13 — TRUST SCORES IN HISTORY MODE USED A STALE COPY OF THE MATHS. The page carried its own inline scorer: score = Σ(delta · decay), with no baseline. That is the IDENTICAL bug fixed in trust.ts on 2026-07-12 (kb:trust-system) — it survived here because the logic was duplicated rather than imported, so the fix never reached the second copy. Every source in History Mode scored near zero. Now calls computeTrustScore: one implementation of trust in the codebase, not two. The lesson is the bug: a fix only propagates as far as the code that shares the function.";
    kpred:honest-note "DECLARED LIMIT (not a bug): a statement with no add/ingest entry in the changelog cannot be dated — graphs seeded from TTL or ingested before the changelog existed have no arrival record. We refuse to guess in either direction: asserting it was present is an unverifiable claim, asserting it was absent is equally unfounded. Undated facts are COUNTED and shown in the UI ('N facts not shown — undateable') rather than silently dropped, which is what the old code did.";
    rdfs:label "History Mode";
    kpred:has-status "production";
    kpred:description "Timeline slider to view graph state at any past timestamp, reconstructed by replaying the changelog — including facts you have since deleted, revived from their tombstones. Trust scores are recomputed as they stood at that instant. Ghost mode in graph.".
kb:trust-system a ktype:Feature;
    kpred:tested-by "src/lib/storage/__tests__/trust.test.ts";
    kpred:has-file "src/lib/storage/trust.ts";
    kpred:known-issue "FIXED 2026-07-12 — CONFIRMING A FACT MADE ITS SOURCE LESS TRUSTED. Trust events are DELTAS (confirm +0.05, reject -0.1), but getTrustScore returned the baseline (0.3 review / 0.8 trusted) ONLY when there were zero events, and the bare SUM OF DELTAS as soon as any event existed. So the first confirmation DISCARDED the baseline: a review source fell 0.3 -> 0.05 for the crime of being confirmed, and a trusted source collapsed 0.8 -> 0.05. It took 16 confirmations just to climb back to where it started. Now: score = baseline + sum(delta * exp(-0.01 * ageDays)), clamped [0,1]. The scoring maths was extracted to src/lib/storage/trust.ts so it could be tested at all — the bug survived because it was tangled with Dexie access inside the store. This is exactly the class of defect the untested-production audit was looking for.";
    kpred:description "Sources carry a trust score in [0,1]: a baseline (0.8 for a trusted source, 0.3 for one awaiting review) moved by the user's own judgements, with confirmations raising it and rejections lowering it roughly twice as hard. Judgements decay exponentially (~1%/day), so recent evidence dominates and a source can recover from a bad patch rather than being condemned forever — and cannot coast indefinitely on old approvals.";
    rdfs:label "Trust System";
    kpred:has-status "production";
    kpred:description "Source trust levels (trusted/review). Auto-confirm for trusted sources.".
kb:rebrand-kb-to-graph a ktype:Decision;
    kpred:tested-by "src/lib/rdf/__tests__/terminology.test.ts";
    rdfs:label "User-facing rename: Graph -> Graph";
