kb:predicate-economy a ktype:Concept;
    rdfs:label "Predicate economy";
    kpred:part-of kb:knowledge-graph;
    kpred:description "A link is judged by its PREDICATE, not by the similarity of the things it joins. Proposing an edge means proposing a specific relation; if no specific relation is true, the honest answer is no edge. The vocabulary of predicates should be small and heavily reused, because a graph's power comes from generalizing across shared relation types — an edge type used once explains nothing.";
    kpred:principle "The predicate is the main clue to a valid link. Label similarity alone is weak evidence; a meaningful relation is strong evidence.", "'is related to' is a non-link wearing the costume of a link. It adds an edge and no knowledge. Prefer NO edge to a generic one.", "Prefer an EXISTING predicate. Mint a new one only when no existing predicate expresses the relation — and never fall back to relates-to when you cannot think of one. Not being able to name the relation IS the finding: it means there probably is not one.", "Graph value leans on the number of connection TYPES more than the number of connections. A predicate used exactly once is a private word: unqueryable, ungeneralizable.";
    kpred:measured "2026-07-13, static/*.ttl: 6016 edges across 237 predicate types (25.4 edges/type). 351 edges (5.8%) are relates-to/related — and in TWO vocabularies at once. 49 of 237 types (21%) are single-use. Enforced by scripts/offline/graph-lint.ts (predicate-economy).";
    kpred:tension "Both failure modes are real and they pull opposite ways: too few types and everything collapses into 'related-to' mush; too many and every edge is a private word. The target is a small vocabulary, heavily reused, each term earning its place.".
